window.MODULES=window.MODULES||{};window.MODULES["cardiac-imaging"]={"slug": "cardiac-imaging", "title": "Nuclear, CT & Cardiac MRI: Multimodality Cardiac Imaging", "tagline": "A fellowship-level framework for choosing and interpreting SPECT/PET, coronary CT, and cardiac MRI — with a deep pathology-recognition atlas of LGE patterns, amyloid, myocarditis, sarcoid, constriction, and ARVC.", "level": 3, "readMin": 44, "takeaways": ["Match the physiology to the test: anatomy (coronary CTA/CAC) answers 'is there disease,' function/perfusion (SPECT, PET, stress CMR) answers 'does it matter,' and tissue characterization (LGE, T1/T2, ECV) answers 'what is the myocardium made of.'", "LGE pattern is the single most discriminating CMR feature: subendocardial-to-transmural in a coronary distribution means infarct, whereas mid-wall or subepicardial LGE sparing the subendocardium means a non-ischemic process. Commit the pattern-to-diagnosis table to memory.", "Cardiac amyloid is a dual-modality diagnosis: CMR shows diffuse subendocardial or transmural LGE, difficult myocardial nulling, and markedly elevated native T1 and ECV (often above 40 percent), while grade 2-3 Tc-99m pyrophosphate uptake with an H/CL ratio at or above 1.5 confirms ATTR only after a monoclonal protein is excluded.", "PET adds absolute myocardial blood flow and myocardial flow reserve (MFR), unmasking balanced ischemia and microvascular dysfunction; global MFR below roughly 2.0 is a powerful, defect-independent adverse-prognosis marker.", "Transmural extent of LGE predicts recovery: segments with under 50 percent scar thickness usually recover function after revascularization, while those over 75 percent rarely do, but STICH and REVIVED-BCIS2 show viability informs rather than mandates revascularization.", "Every non-ischemic cardiomyopathy has a signature: subepicardial inferolateral LGE plus T2 edema (myocarditis, Lake Louise 2018), patchy mid-wall LGE with FDG-PET uptake (sarcoid), pericardial thickening with a septal bounce (constriction), and RV fibrofatty replacement with regional dyskinesia (ARVC)."], "sections": [{"id": "learning-objectives", "title": "Learning Objectives", "body": [{"type": "list", "items": ["Select the appropriate imaging modality based on the clinical question (anatomy vs ischemia vs viability vs tissue characterization) and the pretest probability of coronary artery disease.", "Interpret SPECT and PET myocardial perfusion imaging, including absolute myocardial blood flow and flow reserve, and select and dose pharmacologic stress agents safely.", "Apply coronary calcium scoring, coronary CTA (CAD-RADS), and FFR-CT within appropriate-use and guideline frameworks.", "Recognize ischemic versus non-ischemic late gadolinium enhancement patterns and match each pattern to its specific diagnosis.", "Diagnose cardiac amyloid, myocarditis, sarcoidosis, constrictive pericarditis, and ARVC by their multimodality imaging signatures, and initiate disease-specific therapy.", "Construct a defensible viability and revascularization strategy incorporating STICH, ISCHEMIA, and REVIVED-BCIS2."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "The fellow-level leap in this topic is pattern recognition. A resident asks 'is the stress test positive?' A fellow looks at an LGE image and says 'that subepicardial inferolateral stripe with elevated T2 is myocarditis, not infarct' and changes the entire workup.", "depth": 2}]}, {"id": "why-it-matters", "title": "Why It Matters", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Multimodality cardiac imaging has shifted from a menu of interchangeable stress tests to a physiology-driven decision architecture. The clinical question, not local availability, should determine the test. A fellow reasons from mechanism: what does the myocardium look like, how does it perfuse under stress, and what is it made of at the tissue level."}, {"type": "p", "text": "The stakes are concrete. The <strong>ISCHEMIA</strong> trial showed that in stable patients with moderate-to-severe ischemia, an initial invasive strategy did not reduce cardiovascular death or myocardial infarction versus optimal medical therapy over a median follow-up of about 3.2 years, though it improved angina and quality of life in symptomatic patients. Simultaneously, coronary CTA became a first-line gatekeeper, and CMR tissue characterization now diagnoses conditions (amyloid, myocarditis, sarcoid) that were previously biopsy-dependent or missed entirely.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "The modern skill is not reading one modality well but knowing which modality to <em>not</em> order, and recognizing the handful of tissue signatures that reroute a patient from a coronary workup to a disease-specific pathway (tafamidis or acoramidis for ATTR, immunosuppression for sarcoid, anti-inflammatory therapy for pericarditis).", "depth": 2}]}, {"id": "essential-physiology", "title": "Essential Physiology of Imaging Signals", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Each modality interrogates a different physical signal, and understanding the signal explains both its strengths and its failure modes."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "SPECT tracer uptake", "def": "Technetium-99m agents (sestamibi, tetrofosmin) and thallium-201 distribute proportional to myocardial blood flow and require intact mitochondrial and sarcolemmal viability for retention. Uptake is relative, normalized to the segment with peak counts."}, {"term": "PET tracer kinetics", "def": "Rubidium-82, N-13 ammonia, and the newer F-18 flurpiridaz allow dynamic first-pass quantification, converting count kinetics into absolute myocardial blood flow in mL/g/min via compartmental modeling."}, {"term": "Coronary calcium (CT)", "def": "Calcified plaque attenuates X-rays at a threshold of 130 Hounsfield units; the Agatston score integrates lesion area and peak density as a quantitative surrogate for total atherosclerotic burden."}, {"term": "Gadolinium kinetics (CMR)", "def": "Gadolinium is an extracellular contrast agent that accumulates where the interstitial space is expanded (scar, fibrosis, infiltration) and washes out slowly, producing late gadolinium enhancement on inversion-recovery imaging."}, {"term": "Bone-avid tracer uptake (PYP)", "def": "Technetium-99m pyrophosphate and related bone-seeking tracers bind myocardial transthyretin-derived amyloid deposits, likely via associated microcalcification, giving scintigraphy a near-specific window into ATTR cardiac amyloid."}]}, {"type": "p", "text": "The coronary flow reserve concept underpins all perfusion imaging. Flow reserve begins to decline once a stenosis reaches roughly 50 percent diameter narrowing, but resting flow is preserved by autoregulatory microvascular dilation until the stenosis becomes severe (roughly greater than 85 to 90 percent). Because resting flow stays normal across most of that range, pharmacologic or exercise stress is required to unmask physiologically significant disease.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Relative perfusion imaging reports the <em>worst</em> territory against the <em>best</em>. In balanced three-vessel or left-main disease every territory is underperfused, so relative comparison can look falsely normal. Absolute flow quantification (PET), transient ischemic dilation, a post-stress ejection fraction drop, or increased lung tracer uptake rescues this blind spot.", "depth": 3}]}, {"id": "definitions-and-classification", "title": "Definitions and Modality Classification", "body": [{"type": "table", "head": ["Modality", "Primary signal", "Best answers", "Key limitation"], "rows": [["CAC score (non-contrast CT)", "Calcified plaque burden", "Long-term ASCVD risk refinement", "Misses non-calcified plaque; not for acute chest pain"], ["Coronary CTA", "Luminal anatomy + plaque", "Rule out obstructive CAD (high NPV)", "Blooming from calcium/stents; needs rate control"], ["FFR-CT", "Computational flow modeling on CTA", "Lesion-specific ischemia from one scan", "Requires quality CTA; indeterminate in heavy calcium"], ["SPECT MPI", "Relative perfusion + gated function", "Ischemia in intermediate-risk patients", "Attenuation artifact; balanced ischemia blind spot"], ["PET MPI", "Absolute flow + MFR", "Microvascular disease, balanced ischemia, obesity", "Cost, cyclotron/generator access"], ["Stress CMR", "Perfusion + wall motion + tissue", "Ischemia plus scar in one study, no radiation", "Access, breath-hold, gadolinium/device issues"], ["CMR tissue mapping", "T1/T2/ECV, LGE", "Amyloid, myocarditis, sarcoid, fibrosis", "Expertise-dependent; time-intensive"], ["Tc-99m PYP scintigraphy", "Bone-avid tracer binding to ATTR", "ATTR cardiac amyloid (non-biopsy diagnosis)", "AL amyloid can also take up; must exclude monoclonal protein"]]}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Myocardial flow reserve (MFR)", "def": "Ratio of hyperemic to rest absolute myocardial blood flow. Normal is generally above 2.0; global MFR below roughly 2.0 carries adverse prognosis independent of relative defects, and values below 1.5 mark severe, high-risk physiology."}, {"term": "Extracellular volume (ECV)", "def": "The fraction of myocardium occupied by extracellular space, calculated from native and post-contrast T1 with the patient's hematocrit. Normal is roughly 25 to 30 percent; values often above 40 percent strongly suggest amyloid infiltration."}, {"term": "Native (pre-contrast) T1", "def": "Intrinsic relaxation time before gadolinium. High in edema, fibrosis, and amyloid; low in iron overload and Anderson-Fabry disease."}, {"term": "CAD-RADS", "def": "Standardized coronary CTA reporting: 0 (no plaque) through 5 (total occlusion), with modifiers for stents, grafts, and high-risk plaque, linking stenosis category to management."}], "depth": 2}]}, {"id": "clinical-presentation", "title": "Mapping Presentation to the Imaging Question", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The presenting scenario dictates the imaging axis. Frame every case as one of four questions before choosing a scanner."}, {"type": "steps", "items": ["Stable chest pain, low-to-intermediate pretest probability: 'is there obstructive disease?' Favor coronary CTA for its high negative predictive value.", "Known or higher-likelihood CAD, functional question: 'is ischemia present and how much?' Favor stress perfusion (PET, SPECT, or stress CMR).", "Reduced LVEF with coronary disease: 'is dysfunctional myocardium viable?' Favor CMR LGE or PET perfusion-metabolism imaging.", "New cardiomyopathy of unclear cause: 'what is the tissue made of?' Favor CMR tissue characterization, adding PYP scintigraphy or FDG-PET when amyloid or sarcoid is suspected."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Acute chest pain in the emergency department with low-to-intermediate risk, a non-diagnostic ECG, and a non-elevated troponin is the sweet spot for coronary CTA: a negative study effectively excludes obstructive CAD and enables safe discharge.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Coronary CTA is not a triage tool for suspected ACS with ongoing ischemia, hemodynamic instability, or a rising troponin. These patients need an invasive strategy, not a CT scanner.", "depth": 2}]}, {"id": "diagnostic-approach", "title": "Diagnostic Approach and Test Selection", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Pretest probability, integrated with patient-specific feasibility, drives modality choice. The 2021 ACC/AHA chest pain guideline formalized coronary CTA and stress imaging as parallel first-line options in stable, intermediate-risk patients, with CTA favored in younger patients and when ruling out disease is the goal."}, {"type": "steps", "items": ["Estimate pretest probability of obstructive CAD using age, sex, and symptom character.", "At the low end, consider deferring testing or using CAC to reclassify risk.", "At intermediate probability, choose anatomy (coronary CTA, ideally with selective FFR-CT) or function (stress imaging) based on the specific question and prior data.", "In patients with known CAD or prior revascularization, favor functional imaging to localize the culprit territory.", "Reserve invasive angiography for high pretest probability, refractory symptoms, or clearly high-risk non-invasive testing that will change management."]}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Patient factor", "Steers toward", "Rationale"], "rows": [["Young patient, low calcium", "Coronary CTA", "High image quality, defines non-calcified plaque, low miss rate"], ["Heavy calcification", "PET or stress CMR", "CTA blooming degrades luminal assessment"], ["Obesity, prior attenuation artifact", "PET", "Superior count statistics and routine attenuation correction"], ["Renal dysfunction (avoid gadolinium/iodine)", "SPECT or PET", "No iodinated or gadolinium contrast required"], ["Suspected infiltrative/inflammatory disease", "CMR (+/- PYP or FDG-PET)", "Tissue characterization is unique to CMR; nuclear adds specificity"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Choose the modality that will change your management. If a positive stress test in a stable patient would not lead you to catheterize after ISCHEMIA, ask whether an anatomy-first strategy to intensify prevention is more useful.", "depth": 3}]}, {"id": "spect-pet-perfusion", "title": "DEEP DIVE: SPECT, PET Perfusion, and Pharmacologic Stress", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Nuclear perfusion imaging integrates perfusion, gated function, and ancillary high-risk markers rather than reading the perfusion images in isolation."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Reversible defect", "def": "Perfusion abnormality present on stress but resolving at rest, indicating inducible ischemia in viable myocardium."}, {"term": "Fixed defect", "def": "Defect present on both stress and rest, classically infarct or scar (though attenuation artifact and hibernating myocardium are mimics)."}, {"term": "Transient ischemic dilation (TID)", "def": "Apparent enlargement of the LV cavity on stress relative to rest, a marker of severe or multivessel disease and balanced subendocardial ischemia."}]}, {"type": "p", "text": "Pharmacologic stress uses vasodilators that create flow heterogeneity between normal and diseased beds, or dobutamine when vasodilators are contraindicated. Exercise remains preferred when feasible for its added functional and prognostic data.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Agent", "Mechanism", "Start / usual dose", "Key contraindication", "Major side effects", "Reversal / monitoring"], "rows": [["Regadenoson", "Selective A2A adenosine agonist (coronary vasodilation)", "0.4 mg IV fixed bolus over ~10 s (no titration)", "High-grade AV block without pacing; active bronchospasm (relative)", "Dyspnea, flushing, headache, chest discomfort", "Aminophylline reverses; monitor HR, BP, symptoms"], ["Adenosine", "Non-selective adenosine receptor agonist", "140 mcg/kg/min IV infusion over 4-6 min", "2nd/3rd-degree AV block, sinus node disease, bronchospasm", "AV block, flushing, chest pain, dyspnea", "Stop infusion (half-life seconds); monitor continuous ECG/BP"], ["Dipyridamole", "Blocks adenosine reuptake, raising endogenous adenosine", "0.56 mg/kg IV over 4 min (higher-dose protocols exist)", "Bronchospasm, AV block, hypotension", "Flushing, headache, prolonged effects", "Aminophylline reverses; monitor ECG/BP"], ["Dobutamine", "Beta-1 agonist raising HR, contractility, demand", "Start 5-10 mcg/kg/min, up-titrate to 40; add atropine to reach 85% age-predicted max HR", "Significant arrhythmia, dynamic LVOT obstruction, recent ACS, uncontrolled HTN", "Ventricular/atrial arrhythmia, angina, hypotension", "Short-acting beta-blocker (esmolol) reverses; continuous monitoring"]], "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Hold caffeine and methylxanthines for at least 12 hours before vasodilator stress; they competitively antagonize adenosine receptors and can produce a falsely normal study. Regadenoson does not eliminate this interaction.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic — vasodilator contraindications 'BLAB': Bronchospasm, Low blood pressure, Advanced AV block, Bradycardia/sinus node disease. If any is present, reach for dobutamine instead.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "PET's decisive advantage is absolute flow. A visually normal relative scan with a global MFR of 1.4 signals either diffuse multivessel disease or coronary microvascular dysfunction, both prognostically important and invisible to relative SPECT. MFR is now a first-class prognostic variable.", "depth": 3}]}, {"id": "coronary-ct", "title": "DEEP DIVE: Coronary CTA, CAC, and FFR-CT", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Coronary CT has moved to the front line for stable chest pain because of its exceptional negative predictive value: a normal coronary CTA reliably excludes obstructive CAD and confers an excellent near-term prognosis."}, {"type": "p", "text": "The <strong>coronary artery calcium score</strong> is a non-contrast, low-dose study for asymptomatic risk stratification. A score of zero (the 'power of zero') markedly lowers near-term ASCVD risk and can justify deferring statin therapy in borderline-to-intermediate-risk primary prevention, whereas a high score reclassifies upward and supports intensified prevention.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "table", "head": ["CAC (Agatston)", "Interpretation", "Prevention implication"], "rows": [["0", "No detectable calcified plaque", "Supports deferring/withholding statin in borderline-to-intermediate risk (absent higher-risk features such as diabetes, family history, or smoking)"], ["1-99", "Mild plaque burden", "Favor statin, moderate intensity"], ["100-399", "Moderate burden", "Statin, consider higher intensity"], ["400 or higher (or 75th percentile or above)", "Extensive burden", "High-intensity statin; consider aspirin per bleeding risk"]]}, {"type": "p", "text": "<strong>FFR-CT</strong> applies computational fluid dynamics to a standard coronary CTA to estimate lesion-specific fractional flow reserve without additional scanning, contrast, or stress. A value at or below 0.80 indicates hemodynamic significance, mirroring invasive FFR, and reduces referral of non-obstructive lesions to the catheterization lab, though heavy calcification and motion can render it indeterminate.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Coronary CTA uniquely reports high-risk plaque features that predict events independent of stenosis severity. Mnemonic 'PLaN': Positive remodeling, Low-attenuation plaque, Napkin-ring sign (plus spotty calcification).", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Heart rate and rhythm are everything for CTA image quality. Uncontrolled tachycardia or atrial fibrillation degrades images; premedicate with beta-blockade to a target near or below 60 bpm and give sublingual nitroglycerin for coronary vasodilation unless contraindicated.", "depth": 2}]}, {"id": "cmr-tissue-fundamentals", "title": "DEEP DIVE: CMR Tissue Characterization Fundamentals", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Cardiac MRI is the reference standard for chamber volumes, function, and tissue characterization. Its unique power is distinguishing what the myocardium is made of, using gadolinium enhancement plus parametric mapping."}, {"type": "figure", "src": "../assets/fig/amyloid-cmr.png", "alt": "Cardiac amyloid on CMR", "caption": "Multimodal amyloid diagnosis including CMR late-gadolinium enhancement.", "credit": "Treibel et al. (JCMR 2016) — CC BY 4.0, Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Amyloid_deposition_diagnosis_01.png"}, {"type": "p", "text": "<strong>Late gadolinium enhancement pattern is the master discriminator.</strong> Ischemic scar begins in the subendocardium (the layer most vulnerable to the ischemic wavefront) and extends outward in a coronary artery distribution. Non-ischemic processes typically spare the subendocardium, producing mid-wall or subepicardial enhancement not confined to a vascular territory."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "T2 / T2 mapping", "def": "Sensitive to free water; elevated T2 indicates myocardial edema, the signature of acute injury (acute myocarditis, acute infarct, acute rejection, active sarcoid)."}, {"term": "Native T1 (high)", "def": "Elevated in edema, diffuse fibrosis, and amyloid infiltration."}, {"term": "Native T1 (low)", "def": "Reduced in iron overload and Anderson-Fabry disease, the two classic 'low T1' diagnoses."}, {"term": "ECV", "def": "Extracellular volume fraction. Elevated across fibrotic and infiltrative disease; the highest values, often exceeding 40 percent, characterize cardiac amyloid."}], "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic — the two low native T1 diseases are 'Iron Fab': Iron overload and Fabry. Everything else that alters T1 (edema, fibrosis, amyloid) raises it.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Reference atlas of cardiac MRI late gadolinium enhancement patterns across ischemic and non-ischemic disease. Study the illustrated subendocardial, mid-wall, and subepicardial examples.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: cardiac MRI LGE"}]}, {"id": "lge-pattern-atlas", "title": "PATHOLOGY ATLAS: LGE Pattern to Diagnosis", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "This table is the highest-yield single object in cardiac CMR. Learn to read an LGE image in three steps: which layer (subendocardial vs mid-wall vs subepicardial), which distribution (coronary territory vs not), and what the mapping shows (T2 edema, T1, ECV)."}, {"type": "figure", "src": "../assets/fig/amyloid-pyp.jpg", "alt": "Cardiac amyloid on bone scintigraphy", "caption": "Cardiac uptake on Tc-bone scintigraphy (PYP/DPD family) supporting ATTR cardiac amyloidosis.", "credit": "Hellerhoff — CC BY-SA 4.0, Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Kardiale_Amyloidose_in_der_Szintigrafie_72M_-_NM_-_001.jpg"}, {"type": "table", "head": ["LGE pattern", "Layer / distribution", "Most likely diagnosis", "Differentiating clue"], "rows": [["Subendocardial to transmural, coronary territory", "Inner wall outward, follows LAD/RCA/LCx", "Prior myocardial infarction / ischemic scar", "Respects a vascular territory; matched wall-motion abnormality"], ["Diffuse subendocardial, non-coronary, difficult nulling", "Global subendocardial or transmural", "Cardiac amyloidosis", "Abnormal gadolinium kinetics, high native T1, ECV often above 40 percent"], ["Mid-wall septal stripe", "Intramural, spares endo and epi", "Non-ischemic dilated cardiomyopathy", "Dilated LV; marker of arrhythmic risk"], ["Subepicardial, inferolateral wall", "Outer wall, non-coronary", "Myocarditis (esp. parvovirus/HHV-6)", "Elevated T2 edema; recent viral prodrome"], ["Patchy mid-wall / subepicardial, multifocal", "Often basal septum, mid-wall", "Cardiac sarcoidosis", "FDG-PET uptake in active disease; conduction disease"], ["Focal at RV insertion points", "Junctional (hinge points)", "Pressure overload / pulmonary hypertension", "Non-specific; do not over-call as cardiomyopathy"], ["Circumferential subendocardial (non-amyloid)", "Global inner rim", "Post-transplant vasculopathy, severe microvascular disease", "Clinical context; MFR reduced"], ["Focal mid-wall at hypertrophied segments", "Regions of maximal wall thickness, RV insertion points", "Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy", "Asymmetric hypertrophy; extensive LGE (roughly 15 percent or more of LV mass) informs SCD risk"], ["Basal inferolateral mid-wall/subepicardial LGE with low native T1", "Basal inferolateral wall", "Anderson-Fabry disease", "Low native T1 (glycosphingolipid storage) is the giveaway; LGE appears despite low T1"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic — 'ENDO = ischemia, EPI/MID = the rest.' If the subendocardium is involved and the pattern follows a coronary artery, think infarct. If the subendocardium is spared, think non-ischemic and let the layer and mapping name the disease.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "The one non-ischemic disease that violates the 'spares subendocardium' rule is amyloid, which produces global subendocardial-to-transmural LGE. The rescue is that amyloid also shows difficult nulling and grossly elevated ECV, features an infarct does not, and it is not confined to one coronary territory.", "depth": 3}]}, {"id": "cardiac-amyloid", "title": "PATHOLOGY DEEP DIVE: Cardiac Amyloidosis (CMR + PYP)", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Cardiac amyloidosis is now a treatable disease, so recognizing it is a fellowship imperative. Suspect it with increased wall thickness plus discordantly low ECG QRS voltage, a restrictive filling pattern, bi-atrial enlargement, apical-sparing longitudinal strain on echo (the 'cherry-on-top' bull's-eye), low-flow low-gradient aortic stenosis, or intolerance of standard heart-failure neurohormonal therapy."}, {"type": "p", "text": "<strong>CMR signature.</strong> Diffuse subendocardial or transmural late gadolinium enhancement not confined to a coronary territory, inability to properly null the myocardium on inversion-recovery imaging (blood and myocardium null together, reflecting abnormal gadolinium kinetics from an expanded interstitium), markedly elevated native T1, and ECV commonly exceeding 40 percent (among the highest values seen in any disease).", "depth": 1}, {"type": "p", "text": "<strong>Scintigraphy and the ATTR pathway.</strong> Technetium-99m pyrophosphate (or DPD/HMDP) binds ATTR deposits. Grade the planar heart uptake against bone (Perugini scale) and quantify the heart-to-contralateral-lung (H/CL) ratio at 1 hour. Grade 2 or 3 uptake, or an H/CL ratio at or above 1.5, is positive for ATTR, but only after AL amyloid is excluded, because AL can also take up tracer.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Perugini grade", "Cardiac uptake vs rib/bone", "Interpretation"], "rows": [["Grade 0", "No cardiac uptake, normal bone", "Negative"], ["Grade 1", "Cardiac uptake less than rib", "Equivocal (confirm myocardial retention with SPECT; possible AL or early ATTR)"], ["Grade 2", "Cardiac uptake equal to rib", "Positive for ATTR (if monoclonal protein excluded)"], ["Grade 3", "Cardiac uptake greater than rib, attenuated bone signal", "Strongly positive for ATTR (if monoclonal protein excluded)"]], "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Never diagnose ATTR from a positive PYP scan alone. First exclude a monoclonal protein with serum and urine immunofixation PLUS serum free light chains (SPEP/UPEP alone is insufficient). A positive PYP with a monoclonal gammopathy still requires biopsy, because AL amyloid demands entirely different, urgent hematologic therapy.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "steps", "items": ["Clinical or echo/CMR suspicion of infiltrative cardiomyopathy.", "Screen for monoclonal protein: serum free light chains AND serum/urine immunofixation.", "If no monoclonal protein and PYP grade 2-3 (H/CL at or above 1.5): diagnose ATTR non-invasively.", "If a monoclonal protein is present, or the scan is equivocal: endomyocardial (or surrogate fat/organ) biopsy with amyloid typing.", "Once ATTR is confirmed, genotype (TTR sequencing) to separate hereditary variant (hATTR) from wild-type (ATTRwt)."]}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Drug", "Mechanism", "Start / usual dose", "Key contraindication", "Side effects / monitoring"], "rows": [["Tafamidis", "TTR tetramer stabilizer (prevents fibril formation)", "61 mg (free acid) once daily, or 80 mg tafamidis meglumine once daily", "Pregnancy; more limited benefit in NYHA class IV", "Generally well tolerated; ATTR-ACT showed reduced all-cause mortality and CV hospitalization"], ["Acoramidis", "Near-complete TTR stabilizer", "712 mg orally twice daily", "Pregnancy", "Diarrhea, upper abdominal pain; ATTRibute-CM showed a hierarchical outcome benefit"], ["Vutrisiran", "TTR gene silencing (siRNA)", "25 mg subcutaneously every 3 months", "Hypersensitivity", "Vitamin A supplementation advised; HELIOS-B showed reduced all-cause mortality and recurrent CV events in ATTR-CM"], ["Patisiran", "TTR gene silencing (siRNA)", "0.3 mg/kg IV every 3 weeks (with premedication)", "Hypersensitivity", "Approved for hATTR polyneuropathy; the FDA did not approve it for ATTR cardiomyopathy (APOLLO-B). Vitamin A supplementation advised"]], "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Tafamidis and acoramidis (oral stabilizers) and vutrisiran (subcutaneous siRNA) each have positive cardiomyopathy trials (ATTR-ACT, ATTRibute-CM, HELIOS-B). Diflunisal is an off-label stabilizer whose NSAID renal, GI, and fluid-retention effects limit it in heart failure. Patisiran gained approval for polyneuropathy but not for ATTR-CM.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic — amyloid on the ECG-echo mismatch: 'THICK heart, THIN voltage.' Increased wall thickness with low QRS voltage should trigger the amyloid workup before you call it hypertensive heart disease.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Illustrated examples of cardiac amyloid on CMR (diffuse subendocardial LGE, difficult nulling) and Tc-99m PYP scintigraphy (grade 2-3 myocardial uptake).", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: cardiac amyloidosis"}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "ATTR-ACT trial of tafamidis in transthyretin amyloid cardiomyopathy (mortality and hospitalization outcomes).", "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/", "label": "PubMed: ATTR-ACT"}]}, {"id": "myocarditis-cmr", "title": "PATHOLOGY DEEP DIVE: Myocarditis and the Lake Louise Criteria", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Acute myocarditis classically presents after a viral prodrome with chest pain, elevated troponin, and unobstructed coronaries (a common cause of MINOCA). CMR is the non-invasive reference standard for tissue diagnosis in the stable patient."}, {"type": "p", "text": "<strong>Imaging signature.</strong> Subepicardial or mid-wall LGE that spares the subendocardium and does not follow a coronary territory, most classically in the inferolateral wall (parvovirus/HHV-6); a septal mid-wall or more extensive pattern can carry a worse prognosis. Regional or global T2 elevation reflects edema. A pericardial effusion and impaired systolic function are supportive.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Updated (2018) Lake Louise Criteria", "def": "Diagnosis requires BOTH a T2-based criterion (regional/global T2 elevation or high T2 signal ratio, indicating edema) AND a T1-based criterion (elevated native T1, elevated ECV, or non-ischemic-pattern LGE, indicating injury/fibrosis). Requiring one of each markedly improves specificity over the original single-criterion approach."}, {"term": "Supportive criteria", "def": "Pericardial effusion or pericardial LGE, and LV systolic dysfunction or regional wall-motion abnormality, supportive but not sufficient alone."}], "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic — Lake Louise 2018 is a 'one T2 + one T1' rule: you need edema (T2) AND injury (T1: native T1, ECV, or non-ischemic LGE). One from each column makes the diagnosis.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Fulminant, rapidly progressive, or high-grade AV block myocarditis raises suspicion for giant-cell or necrotizing eosinophilic myocarditis, where endomyocardial biopsy changes management (immunosuppression, transplant/MCS urgency). CMR does not exclude these; do not let a 'viral myocarditis' label delay biopsy in the crashing patient.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Subepicardial and mid-wall LGE of acute myocarditis with matching T2 edema, illustrated CMR examples.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: myocarditis CMR"}]}, {"id": "sarcoid-imaging", "title": "PATHOLOGY DEEP DIVE: Cardiac Sarcoidosis (FDG-PET + CMR)", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Suspect cardiac sarcoidosis in a younger patient with unexplained high-grade AV block, ventricular arrhythmia, or a non-ischemic cardiomyopathy, particularly with known extracardiac sarcoid. Imaging drives both diagnosis and the decisions to immunosuppress and to implant a device."}, {"type": "p", "text": "<strong>CMR</strong> shows patchy, multifocal mid-wall and subepicardial LGE, classically involving the basal septum and the RV side, often with associated wall thinning or aneurysm; LGE marks scar (a substrate for arrhythmia and a poor-prognosis marker). <strong>FDG-PET</strong> demonstrates active inflammation as focal or focal-on-diffuse glucose uptake, and combined perfusion-metabolism patterns stage disease activity and monitor response to therapy.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "FDG-PET for sarcoid is worthless without proper preparation. A prolonged high-fat, very-low-carbohydrate diet (typically 24 hours) followed by a fast of at least 12 hours shifts normal myocardium to fatty-acid metabolism, so residual FDG uptake reflects true inflammation rather than physiologic glucose use. Heparin loading is sometimes added to suppress background uptake.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Drug", "Mechanism / role", "Start / usual dose", "Key contraindication", "Side effects / monitoring"], "rows": [["Prednisone", "First-line anti-inflammatory for active myocardial inflammation", "Typically 0.5 mg/kg/day (about 30-40 mg), then slow taper guided by FDG-PET", "Active untreated systemic infection", "Hyperglycemia, weight gain, bone loss, mood; monitor glucose, BP, bone density"], ["Methotrexate", "Steroid-sparing antimetabolite", "10-15 mg orally once weekly with folic acid", "Pregnancy, significant renal or hepatic disease", "Hepatotoxicity, cytopenias, pneumonitis; monitor CBC and LFTs"], ["Azathioprine", "Steroid-sparing purine analog", "50-150 mg/day (weight-based)", "TPMT deficiency; caution in pregnancy", "Myelosuppression, hepatotoxicity; check TPMT, monitor CBC/LFTs"], ["Infliximab", "Anti-TNF for refractory disease", "Per protocol (IV infusions, weight-based)", "Untreated TB or hepatitis B; advanced HF (TNF inhibitors can worsen)", "Infection, reactivation of TB/HBV; screen before starting"]], "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "The imaging directs two separate decisions. Active inflammation on FDG-PET argues for immunosuppression; extensive LGE scar and a high arrhythmic burden argue for an ICD, per HRS expert consensus, sometimes independent of ejection fraction. Do not conflate 'treat the inflammation' with 'protect against sudden death' — they are distinct pathways.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic — sarcoid FDG prep is 'FAT then FAST': load fatty/low-carb, then fast, so the only glucose-hungry tissue lighting up is inflamed myocardium.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Patchy mid-wall/subepicardial LGE and focal FDG-PET uptake of cardiac sarcoidosis, illustrated examples.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: cardiac sarcoidosis"}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "label": "Cardiac sarcoidosis on CMR — late gadolinium enhancement & T2 (open-access, CC BY)", "text": "LGE and T2 imaging patterns of cardiac sarcoidosis, including the basal and mid-wall / RV distribution that raises the diagnosis", "url": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7860804/"}]}, {"id": "pericarditis-constriction", "title": "PATHOLOGY DEEP DIVE: Pericarditis and Constriction on CMR", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "CMR excels at pericardial disease because it images pericardial thickness, inflammation, and, with real-time cine, the physiology of ventricular interdependence that defines constriction."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Acute pericarditis (CMR)", "def": "Pericardial thickening with bright pericardial late gadolinium enhancement indicating active inflammation; a pericardial effusion may coexist. Pericardial LGE predicts responsiveness to anti-inflammatory therapy and the potential reversibility of constriction."}, {"term": "Constrictive pericarditis (CMR)", "def": "Pericardial thickening (typically greater than 3-4 mm, though constriction can occur with normal thickness), a real-time cine 'septal bounce' (early-diastolic septal shift with respiration from enhanced ventricular interdependence), tethering of the pericardium to myocardium, tubular/conical ventricles, and dilated caval/hepatic veins."}, {"term": "Effusive-constrictive", "def": "Persistent elevation of RA pressure after pericardiocentesis drains an effusion, reflecting a constricting visceral pericardium beneath the fluid."}]}, {"type": "p", "text": "The central differential is constriction versus restrictive cardiomyopathy. Constriction is a pericardial disease with preserved myocardium and exaggerated ventricular interdependence (the septal bounce and respiratory septal shift); restriction is a myocardial disease (often amyloid) with abnormal tissue signal (LGE, high ECV) and no pericardial thickening. This distinction changes management from pericardiectomy to disease-specific medical therapy.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Drug", "Mechanism / role", "Start / usual dose", "Key contraindication", "Side effects / monitoring"], "rows": [["Aspirin or NSAID (ibuprofen)", "Anti-inflammatory for acute/recurrent pericarditis", "ASA 750-1000 mg every 8 h, or ibuprofen 600 mg every 8 h, then taper over weeks", "Active bleeding, peptic ulcer; NSAIDs relatively contraindicated post-MI (use ASA)", "GI bleeding, renal injury; co-prescribe a PPI; monitor renal function"], ["Colchicine", "Reduces recurrence (adjunct to first-line NSAID/ASA)", "0.5 mg twice daily (0.5 mg once daily if under ~70 kg) for 3 months (acute), 6 months (recurrent)", "Severe renal or hepatic impairment; caution with strong CYP3A4/P-gp inhibitors", "Diarrhea, myotoxicity, cytopenias; dose-reduce in renal impairment"], ["Corticosteroid (prednisone)", "Second-line: NSAID-refractory, contraindicated, or autoimmune etiology", "Low-to-moderate dose 0.25-0.5 mg/kg/day with very slow taper", "Should be avoided as first-line (promotes recurrence and steroid dependence)", "Recurrence on taper, metabolic effects; add colchicine to reduce relapse"]], "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic — think of constriction with 'SEPTAL': Septal bounce, Effusive-constrictive possibility, Pericardial thickening, Tethering, Annulus preserved (medial e-prime often paradoxically high, 'annulus reversus'), Ledema/venous congestion. Pericardial LGE means the constriction may still be reversible with anti-inflammatory therapy.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Pericardial thickening and enhancement in constrictive/inflammatory pericardial disease on CMR.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: constrictive pericarditis"}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "label": "Labeled RHC pressure tracings — constriction vs restriction (open-access, CC BY)", "text": "Dean & Kern: the RV dip-and-plateau / square-root waveform and the discordant respirophasic LV–RV pressures that separate constrictive pericarditis from restrictive cardiomyopathy", "url": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11308782/"}]}, {"id": "arvc-imaging", "title": "PATHOLOGY DEEP DIVE: Arrhythmogenic RV Cardiomyopathy (ARVC)", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "ARVC is a desmosomal cardiomyopathy that replaces RV (and sometimes LV) myocardium with fibrofatty tissue, producing ventricular arrhythmias and sudden death in young, often athletic patients. Diagnosis uses the Task Force Criteria, integrating imaging, ECG, arrhythmia, tissue, and family history; no single feature is diagnostic."}, {"type": "p", "text": "<strong>CMR imaging criteria</strong> center on regional RV wall-motion abnormality: akinesia, dyskinesia, or dyssynchronous contraction, combined with either RV dilation (elevated RV end-diastolic volume index) or reduced RV ejection fraction. Fibrofatty replacement and RV aneurysms may be seen, but fat and thin-wall LGE are technically difficult and are not required elements. The classic distribution is the 'triangle of dysplasia': RV inflow, RV outflow, and RV apex.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Do not over-diagnose ARVC from isolated fat or trivial RV wall irregularity; the normal RV has variable trabeculation and epicardial fat, and over-calling ARVC leads to unnecessary ICDs and activity restriction. Conversely, do not exclude it because the RV looks acceptable: modern 'left-dominant' and biventricular arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy can show subepicardial LV LGE (inferolateral, 'ring-like') with a near-normal RV.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic — the ARVC 'triangle of dysplasia' is the RV Inflow, Outflow, and Apex. Regional RV dyskinesia PLUS dilation or reduced RVEF is the CMR major criterion; look also for the epsilon wave and anterior precordial (V1-V3) T-wave inversions on ECG.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "RV dilation, regional dyskinesia, and fibrofatty change of arrhythmogenic RV cardiomyopathy on CMR.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: ARVC"}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Epsilon wave and anterior precordial T-wave inversion of ARVC on the surface ECG.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG Library: ARVC"}]}, {"id": "viability-imaging", "title": "DEEP DIVE: Viability, Hibernation, and Stress CMR", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Viability assessment asks whether dysfunctional myocardium will recover contractile function after revascularization. Two mechanisms produce reversible dysfunction: stunning (transient post-ischemic dysfunction with preserved flow) and hibernation (chronic contractile downregulation from reduced flow)."}, {"type": "table", "head": ["Method", "Viability signal", "Threshold concept"], "rows": [["CMR LGE", "Transmural extent of scar", "Under 50 percent scar likely recovers; over 75 percent rarely recovers"], ["PET (FDG + perfusion)", "Perfusion-metabolism mismatch", "Reduced flow with preserved FDG uptake = hibernating, viable; matched reduction = scar"], ["Dobutamine stress echo/CMR", "Contractile reserve", "Biphasic response (improve at low dose, then worsen) predicts recovery"], ["Thallium redistribution (SPECT)", "Late reuptake", "Redistribution or reinjection uptake indicates viability"]]}, {"type": "p", "text": "The gadolinium technique is elegant: because scar retains contrast and viable myocardium does not, the transmural extent of LGE grades irreversibility directly. Segments with less than 50 percent wall-thickness enhancement usually recover, those exceeding 75 percent are essentially non-viable, and the 50 to 75 percent band is intermediate and often integrates contractile reserve.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "p", "text": "<strong>Stress CMR</strong> combines first-pass perfusion during vasodilator stress with cine wall motion and LGE, delivering ischemia and scar in a single radiation-free examination; quantitative perfusion mapping can additionally estimate myocardial perfusion reserve. A perfusion defect not matched by LGE indicates reversible ischemia rather than infarct.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Viability testing has been humbled by trials. The <strong>STICH</strong> viability substudy did not show that viability status independently identified patients who derived a survival benefit from CABG, and <strong>REVIVED-BCIS2</strong> found that PCI did not improve death or heart-failure hospitalization over optimal medical therapy in ischemic cardiomyopathy with viable, dysfunctional myocardium. Viability informs, but does not by itself mandate, revascularization.", "depth": 3}]}, {"id": "guideline-directed-management", "title": "Guideline-Directed Use and Management Integration", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Imaging exists to change decisions. The framework anchors on the 2021 ACC/AHA chest pain guideline, ISCHEMIA-era interpretation of stable ischemia, and appropriate-use criteria that discourage reflexive or duplicative testing."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Use coronary CTA as a first-line gatekeeper in intermediate-risk stable chest pain, leveraging its negative predictive value and selective FFR-CT for physiology.", "Use functional imaging (PET, SPECT, stress CMR) to localize ischemia and stratify risk, especially with known CAD or prior revascularization.", "Interpret a positive stress test in stable patients through the ISCHEMIA lens: optimize medical therapy first; revascularize primarily for refractory or lifestyle-limiting symptoms, high-risk anatomy, or specific subsets.", "Reserve CMR tissue characterization for cardiomyopathy of uncertain etiology, suspected infiltration, or inflammation, adding PYP scintigraphy for ATTR and FDG-PET for active sarcoid."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Significant left main disease and its equivalents remain a prognostic revascularization indication and were, by design, largely excluded from ISCHEMIA (as were EF below 35 percent and recent ACS). Do not extrapolate the trial's conservatism to unprotected left main disease.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Appropriate-use criteria are a fellowship competency, not a formality. Reordering the same functional test annually in an asymptomatic post-revascularization patient is a classic 'rarely appropriate' pattern that boards and utilization review both flag.", "depth": 3}]}, {"id": "advanced-fellow-concepts", "title": "Advanced Fellowship Concepts", "body": [{"type": "list", "items": ["<strong>INOCA and microvascular disease:</strong> reduced flow reserve (PET MFR or CMR perfusion reserve) with normal epicardial arteries defines coronary microvascular dysfunction, an increasingly recognized cause of angina and adverse outcomes, particularly in women.", "<strong>Balanced ischemia detection:</strong> combine relative perfusion with TID, post-stress LVEF drop, lung tracer uptake, and (on PET) global MFR to avoid missing left-main or three-vessel disease.", "<strong>Low-flow low-gradient aortic stenosis screen:</strong> when the ECG-echo picture suggests amyloid in an AS patient, PYP scintigraphy identifies the dual pathology that changes the TAVR risk discussion.", "<strong>Emerging PET tracers:</strong> F-18 flurpiridaz offers a longer half-life that permits treadmill-exercise PET and higher-resolution flow quantification without an on-site cyclotron or generator.", "<strong>Radiation stewardship:</strong> prefer PET, stress CMR, CZT-camera SPECT, or low-dose CT protocols; track cumulative dose in young patients and those undergoing serial imaging."]}]}, {"id": "bedside-pearls", "title": "Bedside Pearls and Mnemonics", "body": [{"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Difficulty nulling the myocardium on the inversion-recovery LGE sequence is a tactile clue to amyloid before you ever calculate ECV: blood and myocardium null together.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Attenuation artifact mimics fixed defects: breast tissue over the anterior wall and diaphragm over the inferior wall are the classic SPECT culprits; preserved gated wall motion within a 'defect' argues for artifact, not scar.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic — non-ischemic LGE 'layers': subepicardial thinks inflammation (myocarditis), mid-wall thinks non-ischemic DCM or HCM, and diffuse subendocardial that won't null thinks amyloid.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "A coronary calcium score of zero is powerful but not absolute: young patients and acute presentations can harbor non-calcified (soft) plaque that carries zero calcium yet meaningful risk.", "depth": 1}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "A mid-wall septal stripe of LGE in a dilated ventricle marks non-ischemic cardiomyopathy and is associated with arrhythmic events, informing sudden-death and ICD discussions.", "depth": 3}]}, {"id": "common-mistakes", "title": "Common Mistakes", "body": [{"type": "list", "items": ["Ordering coronary CTA for suspected acute coronary syndrome with a rising troponin or ongoing ischemia, delaying appropriate invasive care.", "Calling a relative SPECT study 'normal' in a high-risk patient without checking for TID, post-stress ejection fraction decline, or lung uptake.", "Failing to hold caffeine before vasodilator stress, producing a falsely negative perfusion study.", "Interpreting mid-wall or subepicardial LGE as ischemic scar and missing a non-ischemic cardiomyopathy or myocarditis.", "Diagnosing ATTR from a positive PYP scan without first excluding a monoclonal protein with serum free light chains and immunofixation, missing life-threatening AL amyloid.", "Ordering FDG-PET for sarcoid without proper high-fat, low-carbohydrate dietary preparation, yielding uninterpretable physiologic myocardial uptake.", "Over-calling ARVC from normal RV trabeculation or epicardial fat, or missing left-dominant arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy because the RV looked acceptable.", "Reflexively revascularizing a positive stress test in a stable patient without applying ISCHEMIA-era medical optimization first, and using viability as the sole determinant despite STICH and REVIVED-BCIS2."]}]}, {"id": "references", "title": "References", "body": [{"type": "list", "items": ["2021 AHA/ACC Multisociety Guideline for the Evaluation and Diagnosis of Chest Pain.", "ISCHEMIA Trial (initial invasive vs conservative strategy in stable ischemic heart disease).", "STICH Trial and Viability Substudy; REVIVED-BCIS2 (PCI in ischemic cardiomyopathy).", "Updated (2018) Lake Louise Criteria for CMR diagnosis of myocardial inflammation.", "ATTR-ACT (tafamidis), ATTRibute-CM (acoramidis), and HELIOS-B (vutrisiran) trials; ASNC/AHA multisociety expert consensus on cardiac amyloid imaging (PYP, Perugini grade, H/CL ratio).", "HRS Expert Consensus Statement on cardiac sarcoidosis (FDG-PET, CMR, ICD indications).", "2015 ESC Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Pericardial Diseases.", "2010 Task Force Criteria for the Diagnosis of Arrhythmogenic Right Ventricular Cardiomyopathy."]}]}], "quiz": [{"stem": "A 74-year-old man with heart failure, symmetric increased LV wall thickness, and low QRS voltage on ECG undergoes CMR: diffuse subendocardial-to-transmural LGE not confined to a coronary territory, native T1 and ECV markedly elevated, and the technologist cannot properly null the myocardium. Tc-99m pyrophosphate shows grade 3 myocardial uptake with H/CL ratio 1.9. What is the essential next step before diagnosing ATTR amyloid?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Start tafamidis immediately"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Exclude a monoclonal protein with serum free light chains and serum/urine immunofixation"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Proceed directly to endomyocardial biopsy"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Repeat the PYP scan with SPECT only"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Order invasive coronary angiography"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "A positive PYP scan (grade 2-3, H/CL at or above 1.5) supports ATTR ONLY after AL amyloid is excluded, because AL can also take up bone-avid tracer. Exclusion requires serum free light chains PLUS serum and urine immunofixation. If a monoclonal protein is present, biopsy with typing is mandatory because AL requires urgent, entirely different hematologic therapy. Only after a negative monoclonal screen can grade 2-3 PYP diagnose ATTR non-invasively and justify a stabilizer such as tafamidis or acoramidis."}, {"stem": "A 29-year-old man presents with pleuritic chest pain three days after a viral illness, troponin elevation, and unobstructed coronaries. CMR shows subepicardial LGE in the inferolateral wall sparing the subendocardium, with regional T2 elevation in the same region. Which statement best applies?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "The subendocardial sparing indicates a prior infarct"}, {"key": "B", "text": "This meets the 2018 Lake Louise Criteria for myocarditis (one T2 and one T1 criterion)"}, {"key": "C", "text": "T2 must be normal for a myocarditis diagnosis"}, {"key": "D", "text": "A single LGE criterion alone confirms the diagnosis"}, {"key": "E", "text": "The pattern is diagnostic of cardiac amyloidosis"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Subepicardial inferolateral LGE sparing the subendocardium is the classic non-ischemic myocarditis pattern. The updated 2018 Lake Louise Criteria require BOTH a T2-based marker of edema AND a T1-based marker of injury (native T1, ECV, or non-ischemic LGE). Here regional T2 elevation (edema) plus subepicardial LGE (injury) satisfies one criterion from each column, markedly improving specificity over the original single-criterion approach."}, {"stem": "A 58-year-old man with obesity and a prior non-diagnostic SPECT undergoes rubidium-82 PET. Relative perfusion images look normal, but global myocardial flow reserve is 1.4. What is the best interpretation?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Normal study; no further action needed"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Attenuation artifact from body habitus"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Possible balanced multivessel disease or microvascular dysfunction"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Technical failure requiring repeat imaging"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Definite single-vessel LAD stenosis"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "A normal relative perfusion pattern with a globally reduced MFR (below 2.0, here 1.4) is the classic signature of balanced ischemia from multivessel or left-main disease, or of coronary microvascular dysfunction. Both are prognostically important and can be missed by relative SPECT, which normalizes to the best-perfused segment. Quantitative PET flow is the principal tool that rescues this blind spot."}, {"stem": "A 41-year-old woman with unexplained complete heart block and a non-ischemic cardiomyopathy is evaluated for cardiac sarcoidosis with FDG-PET. Which preparation is essential for an interpretable study?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A high-carbohydrate meal immediately before the scan"}, {"key": "B", "text": "A prolonged high-fat, very-low-carbohydrate diet followed by a prolonged fast"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Caffeine loading to enhance uptake"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Standard hydration with no dietary modification"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Beta-blockade to a heart rate below 60"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Normal myocardium avidly uses glucose and will take up FDG physiologically, obscuring inflammation. A prolonged high-fat, very-low-carbohydrate diet followed by a fast of at least 12 hours (sometimes with heparin) shifts normal myocardium to fatty-acid metabolism, so residual FDG uptake reflects true active sarcoid inflammation. Without this preparation the study is uninterpretable. Beta-blockade and rate control matter for coronary CTA, not sarcoid FDG-PET."}, {"stem": "A 63-year-old man has progressive dyspnea and edema. Echo suggests a filling abnormality but cannot separate constriction from restriction. CMR shows a pericardium 5 mm thick with bright pericardial late gadolinium enhancement, a real-time septal bounce with respiration, and normal myocardial T1/ECV. Which conclusion and implication is correct?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Restrictive cardiomyopathy; refer for pericardiectomy"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Constrictive pericarditis with active inflammation that may respond to anti-inflammatory therapy"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Cardiac amyloidosis; start tafamidis"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Normal study; no pericardial disease"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Acute myocarditis meeting Lake Louise criteria"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Pericardial thickening with a real-time septal bounce (exaggerated ventricular interdependence) and normal myocardial tissue signal indicates constrictive pericarditis, not restriction (which is myocardial and typically shows abnormal T1/ECV, as in amyloid). Bright pericardial LGE signals active inflammation and predicts potential reversibility with anti-inflammatory therapy (NSAID/aspirin plus colchicine, with steroids reserved), potentially avoiding or deferring pericardiectomy."}, {"stem": "A 24-year-old competitive athlete has palpitations, anterior precordial T-wave inversions, and an epsilon wave. CMR shows regional RV dyskinesia with RV dilation and a reduced RV ejection fraction. Which statement is most accurate regarding the diagnosis?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Isolated epicardial fat on CMR alone confirms ARVC"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Regional RV wall-motion abnormality plus RV dilation or reduced RVEF is a CMR major Task Force criterion for ARVC"}, {"key": "C", "text": "A normal-appearing LV excludes any arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy"}, {"key": "D", "text": "ARVC is diagnosed by a single imaging finding without other criteria"}, {"key": "E", "text": "The findings are diagnostic of ischemic scar"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "The Task Force Criteria for ARVC integrate imaging, ECG, arrhythmia, tissue, and family history; no single finding is diagnostic. The CMR major criterion is regional RV akinesia/dyskinesia or dyssynchronous contraction PLUS either RV dilation (elevated RVEDV index) or reduced RVEF. Isolated fat is unreliable and should not be over-called. Note that left-dominant arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy can present with LV subepicardial LGE and a near-normal RV, so a normal RV does not exclude the disease family."}], "references": ["2021 AHA/ACC Multisociety Guideline for the Evaluation and Diagnosis of Chest Pain", "ISCHEMIA Trial (Maron et al., stable ischemic heart disease)", "STICH Trial and Viability Substudy; REVIVED-BCIS2 Trial (PCI in ischemic cardiomyopathy)", "Updated (2018) Lake Louise Criteria for CMR in Myocardial Inflammation", "ATTR-ACT (tafamidis), ATTRibute-CM (acoramidis), and HELIOS-B (vutrisiran) Trials; ASNC/AHA Multisociety Expert Consensus on Cardiac Amyloidosis Imaging", "HRS Expert Consensus Statement on the Diagnosis and Management of Arrhythmias in Cardiac Sarcoidosis", "2015 ESC Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Pericardial Diseases", "2010 Task Force Criteria for the Diagnosis of Arrhythmogenic Right Ventricular Cardiomyopathy"], "guidelines": [{"society": "ACC/AHA", "year": "2021", "text": "In intermediate-risk patients with stable chest pain and no known CAD, coronary CTA is effective for diagnosis, risk stratification, and guiding treatment; stress imaging (PET, SPECT, stress echo, or stress CMR) is a reasonable parallel first-line option.", "cor": "1", "loe": "A"}, {"society": "ACC/AHA", "year": "2021", "text": "Coronary artery calcium testing is reasonable in intermediate-risk (or selected borderline-risk) asymptomatic adults to refine ASCVD risk and guide the primary-prevention statin decision, with a score of zero favoring deferral in the absence of higher-risk features.", "cor": "2a", "loe": "B"}, {"society": "AHA/ACC/HFSA", "year": "2022", "text": "In patients with heart failure of uncertain cause, cardiac MRI with tissue characterization can be useful to identify infiltrative, inflammatory, and other specific cardiomyopathies such as amyloidosis, sarcoidosis, and myocarditis.", "cor": "2a", "loe": "B"}, {"society": "ASNC/AHA (multisociety)", "year": "2019", "text": "In suspected cardiac amyloidosis without a monoclonal protein, grade 2 or 3 myocardial uptake on bone-avid (Tc-99m PYP/DPD/HMDP) scintigraphy is sufficient to diagnose ATTR non-invasively; a monoclonal protein mandates biopsy to exclude AL amyloid.", "cor": "1", "loe": "B"}, {"society": "ESC", "year": "2015", "text": "For acute pericarditis, aspirin or an NSAID is first-line, and colchicine is recommended as an adjunct to improve response and reduce recurrence; corticosteroids are second-line because they promote recurrence and dependence.", "cor": "1", "loe": "A"}]};
